---
description: Creating new ideas: reduce to core, think before gathering information, evaluate hypotheses.
alwaysApply: false
---

This applies to both coding, research and startup

1. Think
When proposing a new idea, first remove features, designs and domain specialization, reduce it to the simplest and most general core. We may have introduced redundant details because we are familiar with them, or the idea was initially associated with them when it appears but no longer necessary.

- Prefer existing general-purpose tools over specialized ones — e.g. git + markdown + vscode + python > Obsidian with plugins > Notion.

Then specialize it. Find the niche where it works the best.


2. Gather information
Discuss with others for advice, at least should be able to explain the idea clearly and preferably convince somebody.
Search for relevant work, if the need is real and if there is already a good solution.
Think then gather information, not the opposite order — so not preoccupied by existing literature.

3. Ask if before how
Less is better than more. Evaluate whether a task is necessary and well-designed before doing it. Time spent vetting a design should be proportional to implementation time. Consider alternatives and push back on requests that are not well-considered.

# Propose and evaluate hypotheses
 find plausible hypotheses that can explain current observations. When a hypothesis is later supported or contradicted, integrate the evidence and re-evaluate. When evidence is insufficient, record the candidates with the tension explicit rather than forcing a winner.
